### **GranTON Q1 Quarterly Report**

# ![][image1]2025 Q1 Tokamak Network(TON) Quarterly Report : 1/1 \~ 3/31

### **Highlight**

In Q1 2025, the Tokamak Network Grant Program continued to support projects that align with our developer-centric vision. With a focus on empowering builders to launch customizable Layer 2 solutions, the GranTON program backed key advancements across staking, governance, cross-chain trade, modular infrastructure, and zero-knowledge technology.

This quarter, progress was driven through projects like the Rollup Hub, which launched a beta version of its appchain deployment SDK and finalized the Thanos mainnet beta. Decentralized components such as random number generation and sybil-resistance systems were enhanced, while governance and staking frameworks saw important updates. These efforts strengthen Tokamak’s goal of offering scalable, modular tools that help developers build Ethereum-based applications more efficiently.

# **1\. Q1 2025 Grant Project Report**

# **1.1 Introduction**

The Tokamak Grant Program (GranTON) supports projects that build a developer-friendly Layer 2 ecosystem. In Q1 2025, selected teams made progress across modular infrastructure, governance tools, and zero-knowledge technologies. This report highlights their key outputs, including appchain SDK releases, protocol research, and core service components that strengthen Tokamak Network’s L2 platform.

# **1.2 Developing Decentralized Staking and Governance(ECO)**

### **Goal**

This initiative aims to enhance Tokamak Network’s staking and governance frameworks by:

* Designing and implementing an upgraded staking system (Staking V2) with slashing mechanisms and fast withdrawals to improve Layer 2 security and increase utility for TON.  
* Deploying a community version of Simple Staking and DAO to promote decentralization, replacing the previously hosted frontend and backend services.

### **Key Features**

* **Staking V2 Development**   
  * Contract upgrades, SDK releases, and frontend redesign to support slashing protocols.  
* **Landing Page Renewal**  
  * New Tokamak Network landing page with integrated partner and price dashboards.

### **Q1 Outputs**

* **Staking V2**  
  * Open [Staking V2 testnet](https://sepolia.staking.tokamak.network/home).  
  * Published Tokamak Economics [Whitepaper v1.1](https://github.com/tokamak-network/papers/blob/master/cryptoeconomics/tokamak-cryptoeconomics-en.md).  
  * [Researched incentive systems](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1wbn85OCC-u2x1M_UMSBwlJdw2c3yu_jk/view?usp=sharing); accepted to [WTSC 2025](https://fc25.ifca.ai/wtsc/).  
* **Landing Page**  
  * [Launched new Tokamak landing page](https://www.tokamak.network/#/) and partners section.  
  * [Integrated price dashboard](https://www.tokamak.network/about/price#/) and deprecated legacy version.

**Q1 Summary and Next Steps**

In Q1, meaningful progress was made in advancing Tokamak Network’s staking and governance systems. Testnet deployment and frontend completion for Staking V2 laid the groundwork for a secure and feature-rich staking experience, while the launch of the new landing page helped improve visibility and developer access. 

In the coming quarter, the focus will shift to finalizing and deploying Staking V2 on mainnet, releasing the community staking edition with developer tools, and gradually rolling out DAO features in line with the network’s long-term vision for decentralized governance.

# **1.3 Tokamak Network Rollup Hub**	

## **1.3.1 Advancing Developer-Centric Appchain Infrastructure(TRH)**

### **Goal**

The Tokamak Rollup Hub project aims to offer a streamlined deployment platform for modular, app-specific Layer 2 blockchains. It supports a wide range of use cases by integrating modular components like bridges, staking, and cross-chain trade features. The long-term goal is to empower developers with customizable tools to launch appchains efficiently, supporting Tokamak’s strategy of a developer-first blockchain ecosystem.

### **Key Features**

* **Deployment SDK**  
  * Enables developers to launch Thanos-based chains with minimal effort.  
* **Staking v2.5 Integration**  
  * Introduced seigniorage functionality for registered appchains.  
* **Cross-Chain Trade Integration**  
  * Demonstrated L2↔L2 swaps with Optimism and Thanos chains.  
* **Website Rebranding**  
  * Updated platform identity and guides for developer onboarding.

### **Q1 Outputs**

* **Deployment SDK (v1)**  
  * [SDK Code](https://github.com/tokamak-network/trh-sdk) | [User Guide](https://docs.tokamak.network/home/~/changes/139/service-guide/rollup-hub/v2/deployment-sdk/how-to-deploy)  
* **Thanos Mainnet Beta Launched**  
  * [Mainnet](https://rolluphub.tokamak.network/deploy/mainnet) | [Docs](https://docs.tokamak.network/home/service-guide/rollup-hub/mainnet-beta) | [Code](https://github.com/tokamak-network/tokamak-thanos-stack)  
* **Cross-Chain Trade MVP**  
  * [Research Article](https://ethresear.ch/t/canonical-cross-chain-swap-fast-and-decentralized-settlement-for-cross-chain-swap-using-canonical-native-l1-l2-messaging/21638) | [GitHub](https://github.com/tokamak-network/crossTrade/tree/L2toL2Implementation)  
* **Staking v2.5 Support**  
  * SDK feature to register L2s for seigniorage eligibility. [PR Link](https://github.com/tokamak-network/tokamak-thanos/pull/324)  
* **Website Rebranding and Documentation**  
  * [Preview](https://dev-rolluphub.vercel.app/) | [Storyboard](https://www.figma.com/design/uXPaDtvFMuI2wOJkMjuXvg/TRH-Re-branding-Storyboard?node-id=123-1079)

**Q1 Summary and Next Steps**

In Q1, Rollup Hub achieved critical progress with the launch of Thanos Mainnet Beta, the rollout of SDK v1 (pending final release), and demonstrated cross-chain transfer capabilities. The rebranding and technical documentation now position TRH as a comprehensive tool for appchain developers.

In Q2, focus will shift to final SDK release, broader appchain deployment support, and integration of components such as staking, cross-trade, and DRB to offer a fully modular experience for builders.

## **1.3.2 Rollup Hub Subproject: Developing a Distributed Randomness Beacon(DRB)**

### **Goal**

The DRB component aims to provide a decentralized and secure random number generation system for appchains within the Rollup Hub. It focuses on delivering trust-minimized randomness through the Commit-Reveal² protocol and supporting seamless integration with a variety of Layer 2 use cases such as gaming, airdrops, and DAO governance.

### **Key Features**

* **Commit-Reveal² Protocol**  
  * Improved randomness protection using randomized reveal order.  
* **EVM-Compatible Support**  
  * Designed for seamless integration with any app-specific L2.

### **Q1 Outputs**

* **Commit-Reveal² Protocol Research Paper Accepted**  
  * [Commit-Reveal² protocol paper](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1wNmlhf7eUjHyhEIndf0QDs8LLEhf0_x3/view?usp=sharing) accepted to [ICBC 2025](https://icbc2025.ieee-icbc.org/), recognizing its contribution to verifiable randomness in blockchain.  
* **Dispute & Error Handling Design**  
  * Developed a formal flow for dispute resolution and error handling based on internal diagrams and shared knowledge.

**Q1 Summary Next Steps**

In Q1, the DRB subproject delivered foundational components of the protocol and was recognized with the acceptance of its Commit-Reveal² research paper to ICBC 2025\.

In the next phase, DRB will be fully integrated into the Rollup Hub SDK, accompanied by comprehensive deployment guides and testing tools to support developers building on Tokamak.

# **1.4 Developing Zero-Knowledge Proof-Based On-Demand Rollups(Ooo)**

### **Goal**

This initiative aims to build an on-demand Layer 2 rollup solution using zero-knowledge proof (ZKP) technology. The goal is to empower even non-experts to launch and operate their own privacy-enhancing Layer 2 networks with ease, aligning with Tokamak Network’s strategy of flexible, user-controlled rollup ecosystems.

### **Key Features**

* **Tokamak zk-EVM**  
  * Enables Ethereum transactions to be transformed into ZK circuits using a front-end “Synthesizer” and a lightweight back-end.  
  * A browser-based UI now allows users to test zk-EVM components without complex setup.  
* **Tokamak zk-Rollup**  
  * Provides privacy by summarizing and obfuscating Layer 2 activity during submission to Layer 1\.

### **Q1 Outputs**

* **Public activity**  
  * Project quarterly news article [posted on Medium](https://medium.com/tokamak-network/tokamak-zk-evm-2024-q4-report-01d91e90c3d8).  
  * Shared technical updates and educational content via Medium and X.  
* **Posted two published study articles**  
  * [Zk-rollup’s gas consumption: Comparative study](https://medium.com/tokamak-network/zk-rollups-gas-consumption-comparative-study-1ee84f923386)  
  * [Zk-Rollup’s Elliptic Curve gas optimization](https://medium.com/tokamak-network/zk-rollups-elliptic-curve-gas-optimization-6520bf4373f1)  
* **Released a user-friendly Synthesizer GUI with token contract support.**  
  * Tokamak zk-EVM: Theory: Front-end algorithms: Packages are distributed through [NPM](https://www.npmjs.com/package/@tokamak-zk-evm/synthesizer)  
  * [Technical guide](https://tokamak-network-zk-evm.gitbook.io/tokamak-network-zk-evm/frontend/synthesizer)  
  * [Graphic user interface](https://github.com/tokamak-network/Tokamak-zk-EVM-playgrounds/blob/main/packages/synthesizer-playground/README.md)

**Q1 Summary and Next Steps**

In Q1, the project advanced significantly in building the technical foundations for user-friendly, ZKP-based rollups. The release of a GUI for the synthesizer and backend library progress brought the team closer to enabling non-experts to interact with zero-knowledge technology. Research outputs and community engagement further strengthened awareness and collaboration around the project.

In the next quarter, the focus will be on completing the remaining components of the Tokamak zk-EVM backend and delivering key algorithms that will allow users to generate zk-proofs for Ethereum transactions—without needing prior ZKP knowledge or specialized hardware. These efforts continue to align with Tokamak Network’s goal of enabling flexible, privacy-focused Layer 2 networks.

# **1.5 Developing a Sybil-Resistance System for Decentralized Applications(SYB)**

### **Goal**

This initiative aims to build a Sybil-resistance system that serves as critical infrastructure for decentralized applications. By integrating with TON, the system is designed to support use cases such as DAOs, social platforms, and gaming, ultimately attracting more users and builders to the Tokamak ecosystem.

### **Key Features**

* **Deployed Sequencer Infrastructure**  
  * A functioning sequencer system deployed on the cloud for testnet-level validation.  
* **Initial Scoring Circuit**  
  * A Circom-based circuit for calculating user uniqueness.  
* **Frontend Explorer**  
  * A live interface for monitoring sequencer activity and on-chain state.

### **Q1 Outputs**

* **ZK Scoring Circuit**  
  * Developed v1 of the scoring algorithm in Circom.  
    * [Scoring Circuit](https://github.com/tokamak-network/tokamak-sybil-resistance-mvp/blob/jjamie65-patch-1/circuits/scoring_circuit_v1)  
* **Sequencer Deployment**  
  * Successfully deployed the basic sequencer package to the cloud.  
    * [Live Preview](https://syb.network/home)  
* **Smart Contracts**  
  * Built testnet transaction interface.   
    * [Sybil Contract](https://github.com/tokamak-network/tokamak-sybil-resistance-mvp/blob/develop/contracts/src/Sybil.sol)  
  * Implemented proxy contract logic.   
    * [Proxy Scripts](https://github.com/tokamak-network/tokamak-sybil-resistance-mvp/tree/proxy-contract/contracts/script)

**Q1 Summary and Next Steps**

In Q1, the Sybil-resistance project reached a major milestone with the successful deployment of its sequencer infrastructure to the cloud. This working MVP lays the foundation for future integration with application-specific Layer 2 networks. Technical components such as scoring logic, proxy contracts, and test interfaces are now in place, making it easier to validate system functionality.

Next, the project will focus on completing the transaction and scoring circuits, improving documentation and deployment guides, and preparing for broader developer access. These developments aim to make Sybil-resistance a practical and modular tool for use across the Tokamak ecosystem.
